–
* co-ordinate, supervise and implement policies of the Council;
* co-ordinate the duties and functions of the National Disaster Management Office;
* advise the National Disaster Controller on all matters pertaining to disaster management activities;
* liaise with and advise Divisional Commissioners and District Officers on disaster management matters;
* liaise with and advise Disaster Service Liaison Officers on disaster management matters;
* supervise and have overall responsibility for the National Emergency Operations Centre and ensure that the Centre is at all times in a full state of readiness for an emergency operation;
* advise and assist agencies and Non-Government Organisations on matters relating to disaster management activities;
* prepare and revise a National Disaster Management Plan, and National Support Plans and initiate training with respect to such plans;
* manage the acquisition and distribution of international assistance provided in response to an emergency situation;
* perform any other functions and duties as directed by the National Disaster Controller.
* supervise and have overall responsibility for the National Emergency Operations Centre;
* disseminate information and advice on matters relating to potential or actual emergency situations; and
* promote, carry out or cause to be carried out the training of personnel for disaster management activities.

(1) The National Disaster Controller will be in overall command when an emergency operations is initiated. He will be assisted by the Divisional Commissioners and District Officers at divisional and district levels.
* All government resources will be at the disposition of the National Disaster Controller during an emergency operation.
* All agencies are subordinate to the National Disaster Controller at their respective levels during an emergency operation.
* Agencies mentioned in the National Disaster Management Plan as being responsible for the issue of hazard warnings in their specific fields shall do so depending on the urgency of the situation.
* An agency which issues a hazard warning shall inform the National Disaster Controller immediately who will in turn convene a meeting of the Emergency Committee.
* All radio stations broadcasting live when a hazard warning is issued under this section shall upon receipt of a warning from the relevant agency or person immediately broadcast messages to the nation or to the areas concerned.
* The National Disaster Controller may employ government, chartered or foreign aircraft to make an aerial survey and assessment of a disaster area.
* The National Disaster Controller nay allocate personnel and equipment immediately to disaster areas and may ask the Commander of the Republic of Fiji Military Forces to allocate military personnel for emergency tasks in such areas.
* the Divisional Emergency Operations Centre shall be the centre for all disaster co-ordination and command at the divisional level;
* all government resources in a division will be at the disposition of the Divisional Commissioner;
* all agencies and persons in a division shall be subordinate to the Divisional Commissioner;
* the District Emergency Operations Centre shall be he centre for disaster operations at the district level;

During an emergency operation -
* all government resources in a district shall come under the disposition of the District Officer;
* all agencies and persons in a district shall be subordinate to the District Officer.
* the evacuation of people in their own interests, or in order to facilitate the necessary operations of the police or military personnel;
* the temporary acquisition or control of any property, undertaking or land;
* the entering and search of any premises;
* the supply and distribution of essential relief supplies, medical assistance, shelter and other resources;
* the maintenance of the means of transportation by land, sea or air and the control of the transport of persons and resources;
* the payment of compensation and remuneration to persons affected by government action or under special powers;
* directing the movements of persons by land, seas or air in the interests of safety;
* prohibiting the unjustified exploitation of a disaster for profit.
